77
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:33,570
If you imagine some sort
of biological complex such

78
00:03:33,570 --> 00:03:36,930
as this kind of monster over here,

79
00:03:36,930 --> 00:03:40,020
you might realize that a lot
of the functionality here comes

80
00:03:40,020 --> 00:03:42,780
from the interface
between different elements

81
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:43,613
of this complex.

82
00:03:43,613 --> 00:03:47,040
So there's intramolecular
interactions between, you know,

83
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:48,960
different parts of the same molecule.

84
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:50,880
There's intermolecular interactions

85
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:52,320
between different molecules.

86
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:54,030
And so this complex is dynamic

87
00:03:54,030 --> 00:03:56,280
and these interfaces
are constantly changing

88
00:03:56,280 --> 00:03:59,430
and it's very hard to
synchronize a large number

89
00:03:59,430 --> 00:04:02,280
of these complexes such
that they're all in phase.

90
00:04:02,280 --> 00:04:07,020
And so if you put a large
number of them into a test tube

91
00:04:07,020 --> 00:04:10,230
and probe it with some
kind of spectroscopy,

92
00:04:10,230 --> 00:04:12,570
you're going to get a mess, right?

93
00:04:12,570 --> 00:04:15,390
A blur because they're all slightly

94
00:04:15,390 --> 00:04:17,310
in a different phase of their motion.

95
00:04:17,310 --> 00:04:19,590
And so if you can grab a single molecule

96
00:04:19,590 --> 00:04:21,480
and actually watch its dynamics,

97
00:04:21,480 --> 00:04:24,360
you can really get an
understanding what is the function

98
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:26,940
and how does the structure
affect the function

99
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:28,800
and what are the dynamics?

100
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:31,350
I would argue the same set of, you know,

101
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:34,080
arguments apply to these
molecular junctions,

102
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:36,270
which are the subject of my talk today,

103
00:04:36,270 --> 00:04:39,000
where you're putting together

104
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,100
at least two very different components

105
00:04:41,100 --> 00:04:43,740
to make some sort of, you know,

106
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:45,630
functional device, if you will.

107
00:04:45,630 --> 00:04:46,950
These are not yet devices.

108
00:04:46,950 --> 00:04:49,620
They're still in basic research
phase of their development,

109
00:04:49,620 --> 00:04:52,140
but they have some sort of functionality.

110
00:04:52,140 --> 00:04:54,900
And this was actually
proposed by Aviram and Ratner

111
00:04:54,900 --> 00:04:56,700
in this seminal paper in the 70s.

112
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:59,340
And what they really kind of focused on

113
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:01,710
and proposed in a revolutionary way

114
00:05:01,710 --> 00:05:04,230
is that you can actually design molecules

115
00:05:04,230 --> 00:05:06,240
to give you electronic functionality,

116
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:08,100
like they can act like, you know,

117
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:10,500
transistors or diodes, and so on.

118
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:12,450
But what I think was underappreciated

119
00:05:12,450 --> 00:05:15,510
for many years is the fact
that the interface here,

120
00:05:15,510 --> 00:05:17,910
which, by the way is
a significant fraction

121
00:05:17,910 --> 00:05:21,450
of the overall size of the
system, can't be ignored,

122
00:05:21,450 --> 00:05:24,060
because the interface

123
00:05:24,060 --> 00:05:25,410
is on the same length scale

124
00:05:26,340 --> 00:05:29,460
as the system itself and so
you can't just neglect it.

125
00:05:29,460 --> 00:05:30,960
The dynamics of this interface

126
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:32,880
will influence the properties.

127
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:36,000
And so you really wanna be able
to isolate this and study it

128
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:38,790
and see how changing structures affect

129
00:05:38,790 --> 00:05:42,000
the electronic properties
of the entire circuit.

130
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:45,360
What makes these systems really

131
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:48,060
unique opportunity, I think,

132
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:51,240
is that you can see quantum effects

133
00:05:51,240 --> 00:05:53,010
even at room temperature.

134
00:05:53,010 --> 00:05:54,480
Why is, and that's really kind of

135
00:05:54,480 --> 00:05:56,940
what I will be focusing
on today, so why is that?

136
00:05:56,940 --> 00:05:59,250
Well, at the nanometer scale,

137
00:05:59,250 --> 00:06:01,170
if you think about the mean free path

138
00:06:01,170 --> 00:06:03,090
of an electron in a metal,

139
00:06:03,090 --> 00:06:04,920
it's a lot longer than a nanometer.

140
00:06:04,920 --> 00:06:06,090
So what does that mean?

141
00:06:06,090 --> 00:06:08,460
That means that on the
scale of the junction,

142
00:06:08,460 --> 00:06:11,190
the electron crosses the
junction ballistically

143
00:06:11,190 --> 00:06:13,470
without scattering off of phonons.

144
00:06:13,470 --> 00:06:16,620
And so because there's no
scattering on this length scale,

145
00:06:16,620 --> 00:06:18,780
the process, this transport of an electron

146
00:06:18,780 --> 00:06:20,850
across the junction is coherent.

147
00:06:20,850 --> 00:06:23,130
Oops. There's the arrow.

148
00:06:23,130 --> 00:06:26,850
And so even at room temperature,
this coherence is preserved

149
00:06:26,850 --> 00:06:29,520
and we can observe quantum phenomena,

150
00:06:29,520 --> 00:06:32,760
like quantum interference
and then also use chemistry

151
00:06:32,760 --> 00:06:34,620
by manipulating, synthetically,

152
00:06:34,620 --> 00:06:36,390
the structure of this molecule

153
00:06:36,390 --> 00:06:39,960
to control and engineer quantum phenomena.

154
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:43,330
Okay, so just another

155
