00:07:04,410 --> 00:07:07,080
For longer molecules and softer materials,

164
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:08,877
we actually use the optical tweezer,

165
00:07:08,877 --> 00:07:12,210
and these two tools are
really kind of complimentary

166
00:07:12,210 --> 00:07:15,900
in that they cover, they span
different regimes of length

167
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:17,550
and also of energy.

168
00:07:17,550 --> 00:07:19,290
So the scanning probe technique

169
00:07:19,290 --> 00:07:22,560
is really ideal for small
molecules on the nano scale,

170
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:25,170
because it has exquisite length resolution

171
00:07:25,170 --> 00:07:27,570
and it is quite a stiff probe,

172
00:07:27,570 --> 00:07:30,240
which is compatible with
the covalent linkages

173
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:31,980
in these short molecules.

174
00:07:31,980 --> 00:07:34,830
In contrast, if you wanna study, you know,

175
00:07:34,830 --> 00:07:35,880
Van der Waals-bonded

176
00:07:35,880 --> 00:07:39,090
or hydrogen-bonded softer materials,

177
00:07:39,090 --> 00:07:41,880
you need a softer probe
on the piconewton scale.

178
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:43,470
This is also the scale that's ideal

179
00:07:43,470 --> 00:07:45,840
for probing biological complexes.

180
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:48,810
And you can sacrifice a little
bit of your length resolution

181
00:07:48,810 --> 00:07:50,820
because these are extended systems.

182
00:07:50,820 --> 00:07:53,850
So these are really two nice
complimentary approaches

183
00:07:53,850 --> 00:07:55,380
and we use them both in the lab.

