199
00:08:35,550 --> 00:08:39,090
Okay, so as I already mentioned,

200
00:08:39,090 --> 00:08:41,940
what I will tell you about
are these molecular junctions

201
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:43,260
and how we can observe

202
00:08:43,260 --> 00:08:46,470
and control quantum
phenomena in these systems.

203
00:08:46,470 --> 00:08:48,870
So one of the very few

204
00:08:48,870 --> 00:08:51,450
kind of background
theory slides I promised,

205
00:08:51,450 --> 00:08:54,720
but, so I already mentioned
that transport here

206
00:08:54,720 --> 00:08:58,680
is ballistic, so this is not
like in a macroscopic system

207
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:00,630
where electron gas diffuses.

208
00:09:00,630 --> 00:09:03,870
That's kind of the model
of conductivity here,

209
00:09:03,870 --> 00:09:05,817
the electron crosses ballistically,

210
00:09:05,817 --> 00:09:08,250
and that means that
transport here is described

211
00:09:08,250 --> 00:09:12,210
by the Landauer-Buttiker
model where conductance,

212
00:09:12,210 --> 00:09:15,360
this G's conductance,
current divided by voltage,

213
00:09:15,360 --> 00:09:16,830
so the inverse of what you're used

214
00:09:16,830 --> 00:09:19,110
to reading about resistance,

215
00:09:19,110 --> 00:09:21,390
that's just the convention in this field.

216
00:09:21,390 --> 00:09:25,770
Conductance is going to
depend on the transmission T

217
00:09:25,770 --> 00:09:29,190
of the available quantum
channels in your junction.

218
00:09:29,190 --> 00:09:31,050
So if there are many quantum channels,

219
00:09:31,050 --> 00:09:32,490
then you sum over them,

220
00:09:32,490 --> 00:09:34,740
and you sum over this coefficient T,

221
00:09:34,740 --> 00:09:37,167
the transmittance of this junction.

222
00:09:37,167 --> 00:09:39,840
And so if you have a
single conducting channel

223
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:42,630
with a transmission probability of 100%,

224
00:09:42,630 --> 00:09:45,510
then you expect a conductance of one G0,

225
00:09:45,510 --> 00:09:48,780
which is the quantum of
conductance through this junction.

226
00:09:48,780 --> 00:09:51,570
So it turns out that
molecules typically have

227
00:09:51,570 --> 00:09:53,070
a transmission probability

228
00:09:53,070 --> 00:09:55,470
that's lower than 100%.

229
00:09:55,470 --> 00:09:56,580
And why is that?

230
00:09:56,580 --> 00:10:00,330
Well, if we kind of do the
kind of the most simple model

231
00:10:00,330 --> 00:10:05,130
of what this system is, we
have two metal electrodes,

232
00:10:05,130 --> 00:10:09,690
which have a continuum of
energy states filled up

233
00:10:09,690 --> 00:10:11,160
to this energy E fermi,

234
00:10:11,160 --> 00:10:14,100
so all my carriers of charge are

235
00:10:14,100 --> 00:10:16,320
at the energy called E fermi.

236
00:10:16,320 --> 00:10:19,830
Of course we apply a slide bias
which is greatly exaggerated

237
00:10:19,830 --> 00:10:22,860
in this cartoon to drive the
system out of equilibrium

238
00:10:22,860 --> 00:10:25,320
and drive electrons across this junction,

239
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:27,990
but now as this electron
comes to this junction,

240
00:10:27,990 --> 00:10:29,310
what it sees actually

241
00:10:29,310 --> 00:10:32,520
are these discrete molecular
orbitals from the molecule.

242
00:10:32,520 --> 00:10:34,380
The molecule's like a zero-D system,

243
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:38,370
so it has these discreet spectrum.

244
00:10:38,370 --> 00:10:41,220
And so these orbitals
are typically mismatched

245
00:10:41,220 --> 00:10:44,130
in energy from the fermi energy of gold

246
00:10:44,130 --> 00:10:46,110
and so what you really have here is kind

247
00:10:46,110 --> 00:10:47,850
of your classic tunneling problem,

248
00:10:47,850 --> 00:10:50,130
which maybe you remember
from back, you know,

249
00:10:50,130 --> 00:10:52,950
introductory quantum classes
where the electron's going

250
00:10:52,950 --> 00:10:55,110
to tunnel across this barrier.

251
00:10:55,110 --> 00:10:59,460
And so the tunneling
probability is exponentially,

252
00:10:59,460 --> 00:11:02,130
decays exponentially with
the length of the molecule.

253
00:11:02,130 --> 00:11:03,960
The longer the barrier,

254
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:06,120
the lower the transmission probability.

255
00:11:06,120 --> 00:11:07,830
And the other thing that it depends on

256
00:11:07,830 --> 00:11:09,780
is the height of the barrier.

257
00:11:09,780 --> 00:11:10,620
And in this case,

258
00:11:10,620 --> 00:11:13,710
the height of the barrier
is the energy mismatch

259
00:11:13,710 --> 00:11:15,300
between the molecular orbital,

260
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:18,270
so I should mention, I'm
using chemistry language here.

261
00:11:18,270 --> 00:11:20,670
So MO is molecular orbital.

262
00:11:20,670 --> 00:11:23,460
These are just eigenstates
of the molecular system.

263
00:11:23,460 --> 00:11:26,760
And then the LUMO is the lowest
unoccupied molecular orbital

264
00:11:26,760 --> 00:11:29,340
and this is HOMO, highest
occupied molecular orbital.

265
00:11:29,340 --> 00:11:31,620
This is just chemistry jargon,

266
00:11:31,620 --> 00:11:35,550
but the mismatch is what dictates
the height of the barrier

267
00:11:35,550 --> 00:11:39,360
and so your conductance will decay faster

268
00:11:39,360 --> 00:11:43,503
for molecules that have a wider
HOMO-LUMO gap, for example.

269
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:47,520
So that's one way to think about this.

270
00:11:47,520 --> 00:11:48,660
There's kind of another way

271
00:11:48,660 --> 00:11:51,060
to think about transmission in the system

272
00:11:51,060 --> 00:11:55,500
and that's by realizing that
these discreet resonances

273
00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:57,810
will broaden when the molecule interacts

274
00:11:57,810 --> 00:11:58,643
with the metal, right?

275
00:11:58,643 --> 00:12:01,890
So the molecular orbitals
will hybridize with the metal

276
00:12:01,890 --> 00:12:04,440
and so the lifetime will shorten

277
00:12:04,440 --> 00:12:08,820
and so these resonances will
broaden and it's the broadening

278
00:12:08,820 --> 00:12:11,860
and the resulting overlap of this resonant

279
00:12:12,960 --> 00:12:16,500
of this kind of molecular
orbital resonance,

280
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:20,190
the orbital overlap at fermi
will dictate transmission.

281
00:12:20,190 --> 00:12:22,650
So energy level alignment is important

282
00:12:22,650 --> 00:12:24,270
and broadening is also important

283
00:12:24,270 --> 00:12:26,100
for determining transmission.

284
00:12:26,100 --> 00:12:28,950
And this spectrum on
the right we often get

285
00:12:28,950 --> 00:12:30,360
from calculations, for example,

286
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:32,430
density functional theory calculations

287
00:12:32,430 --> 00:12:35,220
and we will often calculate
this and then compare

288
00:12:35,220 --> 00:12:38,700
to our experimental
measurements of conductance.

289
00:12:38,700 --> 00:12:41,040
Okay, so how do we do these measurements?

290
00:12:41,040 --> 00:12:42,840
I will go through this rather quickly.

291
00:12:42,840 --> 00:12:45,840
It's a modified scanning tunneling
microscope except instead

292
00:12:45,840 --> 00:12:49,020
of imaging to get a image in 2D,

293
00:12:49,020 --> 00:12:53,640
we're going to operate this
in the I of Z kind of mode

294
00:12:53,640 --> 00:12:57,900
where Z is the axis
perpendicular to the surface

295
00:12:57,900 --> 00:12:59,190
and so we're just gonna smash

296
00:12:59,190 --> 00:13:02,040
and then pull out this tip
relative to the substrate

297
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:04,290
and we're going to do
that thousands of times.

298
00:13:04,290 --> 00:13:07,260
And if we do this in a solution
of molecules occasionally,

299
00:13:07,260 --> 00:13:09,900
we trap a molecule in this junction

300
00:13:09,900 --> 00:13:12,060
and we measure the current.

301
00:13:12,060 --> 00:13:14,490
Okay, we can do this at
room temperature, as I said.

302
00:13:14,490 --> 00:13:16,890
We also do this at times at four kelvin

303
00:13:16,890 --> 00:13:19,110
and we collect many measurements

304
00:13:19,110 --> 00:13:21,870
to get statistically meaningful results.

305
00:13:21,870 --> 00:13:24,210
Okay, am I doing okay with the microphone?

306
00:13:24,210 --> 00:13:25,680
Yes. Okay, good.

307
00:13:25,680 --> 00:13:27,030
So how do, you know,

308
00:13:27,030 --> 00:13:29,040
how do you know that what
I'm telling you is correct?

309
00:13:29,040 --> 00:13:30,150
We'll just look at the data.

310
00:13:30,150 --> 00:13:34,560
So here's a single pullout
trace measured on clean gold.

311
00:13:34,560 --> 00:13:36,270
And so immediately what you see

312
00:13:36,270 --> 00:13:39,270
is you have these discreet
jumps in conductance.

313
00:13:39,270 --> 00:13:41,370
This is very kind of not classical.

314
00:13:41,370 --> 00:13:43,050
Why are there discreet jumps?

315
00:13:43,050 --> 00:13:44,430
Because a single gold atom

316
00:13:44,430 --> 00:13:48,600
has one nearly perfectly
transmitting conductance channel.

317
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:51,540
So as you pull this junction
apart, you thin out the number

318
00:13:51,540 --> 00:13:53,490
of gold atoms in the cross section

319
00:13:53,490 --> 00:13:55,560
and you're removing conducting channels

320
00:13:55,560 --> 00:13:59,460
and so your conductance
drops in these jumps

321
00:13:59,460 --> 00:14:01,950
of integer multiples of G0.

322
00:14:01,950 --> 00:14:03,900
This is very nice because at the very end,

323
00:14:03,900 --> 00:14:06,030
you have this plateau at one G0

324
00:14:06,030 --> 00:14:08,580
and when it ruptures, you open up this gap

325
00:14:08,580 --> 00:14:10,020
and you know it's pristine,

326
00:14:10,020 --> 00:14:11,760
because you just had a signature

327
00:14:11,760 --> 00:14:13,260
of a single quantum point contact,

328
00:14:13,260 --> 00:14:15,390
a single gold atom at the junction.

329
00:14:15,390 --> 00:14:17,130
Okay, I'm just going to zoom in

330
00:14:17,130 --> 00:14:19,560
and show this to you
on a logarithmic scale

331
00:14:19,560 --> 00:14:21,450
so that you can see that after you rupture

332
00:14:21,450 --> 00:14:24,090
that final plateau, conductance drops,

333
00:14:24,090 --> 00:14:25,950
and then you have this kind of tunneling

334
00:14:25,950 --> 00:14:29,430
through the vacuum gap
that you might expect.

335
00:14:29,430 --> 00:14:31,170
Okay, we do this, as I said,

336
00:14:31,170 --> 00:14:34,410
thousands of times to get
statistically meaningful results

337
00:14:34,410 --> 00:14:37,683
and we analyze the data by
constructing histograms.

338
00:14:38,550 --> 00:14:40,290
Okay, there we go.

339
00:14:40,290 --> 00:14:41,483
This is a histogram

340
00:14:41,483 --> 00:14:45,300
of 1,000 traces measured on
clean gold at room temperature.

341
00:14:45,300 --> 00:14:48,060
And so, you know, we don't
select any of our data.

342
00:14:48,060 --> 00:14:50,280
We bin every single trace we measure,

343
00:14:50,280 --> 00:14:52,110
we put into this histogram.

344
00:14:52,110 --> 00:14:53,970
And so the fact that we have peaks

345
00:14:53,970 --> 00:14:56,190
at integer multiples of G0 means

346
00:14:56,190 --> 00:14:57,120
that I didn't just select

347
00:14:57,120 --> 00:14:59,460
a very pretty-looking
trace for you on the left.

348
00:14:59,460 --> 00:15:01,680
I do in fact, very often, in fact,

349
00:15:01,680 --> 00:15:04,110
in every single trace measure plateaus

350
00:15:04,110 --> 00:15:07,110
at those integer multiples of G0

351
00:15:07,110 --> 00:15:08,820
and this is my tunneling signature.

352
00:15:08,820 --> 00:15:11,220
Okay, so now we're ready
to introduce molecules.

353
00:15:11,220 --> 00:15:14,100
And so we're going to put molecules

354
00:15:14,100 --> 00:15:15,780
that have been terminated, I apologize,

355
00:15:15,780 --> 00:15:17,580
there's a little bit of a lag here.

356
00:15:17,580 --> 00:15:18,413
There we go,

357
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:21,690
that have been functionalized

358
00:15:21,690 --> 00:15:26,010
by some sort of linker group
that we know binds to gold.

359
00:15:26,010 --> 00:15:28,320
Okay, so in this case it's the nitrogen

360
00:15:28,320 --> 00:15:29,640
and the mean linker group.

361
00:15:29,640 --> 00:15:32,850
And so what we see now is that
following the one G0 plateau,

362
00:15:32,850 --> 00:15:33,990
we very often start

363
00:15:33,990 --> 00:15:38,220
to see additional plateaus at
lower values of conductance.

364
00:15:38,220 --> 00:15:41,400
And if we bin every
single trace we measure,

365
00:15:41,400 --> 00:15:43,260
this is 10,000 traces, I believe,

366
00:15:43,260 --> 00:15:44,970
we start to see peaks

367
00:15:44,970 --> 00:15:48,000
at molecule-specific conductance values.

368
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:49,650
You know, to give you a
little bit more evidence

369
00:15:49,650 --> 00:15:52,140
that these are really
single molecule signatures,

370
00:15:52,140 --> 00:15:54,210
I will point out that
there's a shoulder here

371
00:15:54,210 --> 00:15:56,340
and if you fit the
position of this shoulder,

372
00:15:56,340 --> 00:15:59,850
its conductance is exactly
double the conductance

373
00:15:59,850 --> 00:16:01,590
of the main peak.

374
00:16:01,590 --> 00:16:03,240
I should say that actually this question

375
00:16:03,240 --> 00:16:05,100
of is this a single molecule or not

376
00:16:05,100 --> 00:16:08,760
has largely been settled
over the last 20 years or so.

377
00:16:08,760 --> 00:16:11,640
This field is kind of reaching maturity.

378
00:16:11,640 --> 00:16:15,630
Okay, so there's one more
piece of kind of tool set

379
00:16:15,630 --> 00:16:18,390
that I have to show you,
which is another way

380
00:16:18,390 --> 00:16:21,300
that we analyze this
data is by constructing

381
00:16:21,300 --> 00:16:23,820
what we call 2D histograms where we now,

382
00:16:23,820 --> 00:16:25,920
instead of just looking at the conductance

383
00:16:25,920 --> 00:16:27,930
and bending the conductance axis,

384
00:16:27,930 --> 00:16:31,470
we're going to align all our
traces along the sharp rupture

385
00:16:31,470 --> 00:16:33,630
and kind of add them
all on top of each other

386
00:16:33,630 --> 00:16:35,610
to create a sort of heat map.

387
00:16:35,610 --> 00:16:38,490
So now we've bend both the conductance

388
00:16:38,490 --> 00:16:40,410
as well as the displacement axis.

389
00:16:40,410 --> 00:16:44,190
So this tells us on average,
as you pull the junction apart,

390
00:16:44,190 --> 00:16:46,410
not only what is the average conductance,

391
00:16:46,410 --> 00:16:49,410
but also how long on average
does this molecule stay

392
00:16:49,410 --> 00:16:52,803
in the junction before the
whole junction falls apart.

393
00:16:53,850 --> 00:16:55,440
Okay, so these are 2D histograms.

394
00:16:55,440 --> 00:16:57,450
And then here on the right you can see,

395
00:16:57,450 --> 00:16:58,830
I don't think you can see my pointer,

396
00:16:58,830 --> 00:17:01,440
but a 1D histogram turned on its side.

397
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:03,150
Okay, I hope that's clear enough.

398
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:05,640
And so now we can do
some interesting stuff.

399
00:17:05,640 --> 00:17:08,430
So this technique is very sensitive

400
00:17:08,430 --> 00:17:10,230
to the structure of the molecule.

401
00:17:10,230 --> 00:17:12,800
So for example, if I measure
conductance of molecules

402
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:15,750
of different lengths,
here measuring conductance

403
00:17:15,750 --> 00:17:18,120
of alkanes all terminated
with the nitrogen,

404
00:17:18,120 --> 00:17:21,060
you see that the conductance
decays with length.

405
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:24,150
Of course we make histograms
and we look at the average.

406
00:17:24,150 --> 00:17:26,340
And indeed once this appears,

407
00:17:26,340 --> 00:17:29,010
you will see that the conductance decays,

408
00:17:29,010 --> 00:17:32,133
as we predicted,
exponentially with length.

409
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:38,313
I see it on my computer.

410
00:17:40,590 --> 00:17:41,970
I think it just needs a moment.

411
00:17:41,970 --> 00:17:45,508
So it decays exponentially
with length. There you go.

412
00:17:45,508 --> 00:17:46,950
(chuckles) There it is.

413
00:17:46,950 --> 00:17:48,213
And, you know,

414
00:17:49,440 --> 00:17:52,860
as expected, so this is tunneling, right?

415
00:17:52,860 --> 00:17:55,353
Quantum tunneling, and it went too far.

416
00:17:56,700 --> 00:17:59,910
And the other kind of interesting thing

417
00:17:59,910 --> 00:18:01,650
is that the decay depends

418
00:18:01,650 --> 00:18:04,260
on which molecular family you probe.

419
00:18:04,260 --> 00:18:07,260
So oligophenylling, so oligophenyls,

420
00:18:07,260 --> 00:18:09,750
which I don't know who the audience is,

421
00:18:09,750 --> 00:18:12,180
so I think it's kind of
obvious for a chemist.

422
00:18:12,180 --> 00:18:15,210
But, you know, I think we
all kinda have intuition

423
00:18:15,210 --> 00:18:16,500
that this little benzene ring,

424
00:18:16,500 --> 00:18:18,660
which is kind of the basic
building block of graphene,

425
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:23,430
has the localized pi system,
which in graphene results in,

426
00:18:23,430 --> 00:18:25,650
you know, a lot of the
properties of graphene.

427
00:18:25,650 --> 00:18:28,410
And in this case, this
delocalized pi system means

428
00:18:28,410 --> 00:18:31,200
that this set of molecules
is more conductive than

429
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:32,970
the saturated set of molecules

430
00:18:32,970 --> 00:18:35,370
and so the conductance decays more slowly.

431
00:18:35,370 --> 00:18:36,750
And so this is kind of interesting,

432
00:18:36,750 --> 00:18:38,970
this is signature of pi transport,

433
00:18:38,970 --> 00:18:40,980
whereas this sharper decay is signature

434
00:18:40,980 --> 00:18:42,060
of sigma transport.

435
00:18:42,060 --> 00:18:44,550
And so you can kind of
understand which one

436
00:18:44,550 --> 00:18:46,533
is which by looking at these trends.

437
00:18:47,460 --> 00:18:49,680
Okay, so this is quantum tunneling

438
00:18:49,680 --> 00:18:52,830
and this is so sensitive
to the molecular structure

439
00:18:52,830 --> 00:18:55,290
that something that we're
working on in my lab,

440
00:18:55,290 --> 00:18:57,600
I won't tell you about it in detail today,

441
00:18:57,600 --> 00:18:59,910
but using this technique for biosensing.

442
00:18:59,910 --> 00:19:02,940
So, for example, we've shown
that we can distinguish signals

443
00:19:02,940 --> 00:19:06,180
from adenine and adenosine, for example.

444
00:19:06,180 --> 00:19:08,640
And so we're working to see
whether we can apply this

445
00:19:08,640 --> 00:19:10,500
to other bio-sensing applications.

446
00:19:10,500 --> 00:19:13,290
It's a sort of new spectroscopy, okay.

447
00:19:13,290 --> 00:19:14,970
So the main subject of my talk

448
00:19:14,970 --> 00:19:17,910
is engineering quantum properties

449
00:19:17,910 --> 00:19:20,220
in these molecular
circuits with chemistry.

450
00:19:20,220 --> 00:19:22,210
And I first will tell you a story about

451
00:19:23,160 --> 00:19:25,410
how we can create a single molecule switch

452
00:19:25,410 --> 00:19:30,240
or a single molecule sensor,
depending on your perspective,

453
00:19:30,240 --> 00:19:33,810
by manipulating quantum
interference in these junctions.

454
00:19:33,810 --> 00:19:37,830
So to do this, I actually have
to tell you that, you know,

455
00:19:37,830 --> 00:19:40,680
I held something back and I
didn't tell you another thing

456
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:43,200
that's important in determining transport

457
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:44,033
in these junctions.

458
00:19:44,033 --> 00:19:45,900
So I told you about energy level alignment

459
00:19:45,900 --> 00:19:49,170
and level broadening that
results in this broadening here,

460
00:19:49,170 --> 00:19:53,340
but if my claim is correct,
the transport here is coherent,

461
00:19:53,340 --> 00:19:55,710
then symmetry will be important,

462
00:19:55,710 --> 00:19:58,980
because this electron wave incident

463
00:19:58,980 --> 00:20:01,260
on the junction can tunnel across both

464
00:20:01,260 --> 00:20:04,170
or more than two molecular orbitals

465
00:20:04,170 --> 00:20:06,540
as long as they're nearby in energy.

466
00:20:06,540 --> 00:20:09,780
And whether or not the transmitted wave

467
00:20:09,780 --> 00:20:11,550
will interfere constructively

468
00:20:11,550 --> 00:20:16,110
with itself after it crosses
these two available kind of,

469
00:20:16,110 --> 00:20:19,110
you know, channels or destructively,

470
00:20:19,110 --> 00:20:23,613
that depends on the symmetry
of these molecular orbitals.

471
00:20:24,720 --> 00:20:27,420
So, really, if this seems mysterious,

472
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:30,235
it's actually just a property
of the fact that this is,

473
00:20:30,235 --> 00:20:31,530
you know, a quantum phenomenon.

474
00:20:31,530 --> 00:20:34,080
And so if we wanna look at
the transmission probability,

475
00:20:34,080 --> 00:20:36,000
we have to square the amplitude.

476
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,250
And in this case, the
amplitude is actually a sum

477
00:20:38,250 --> 00:20:41,190
of two amplitudes and so
if you square them here,

478
00:20:41,190 --> 00:20:43,620
you're going to always
get an interference term.

479
00:20:43,620 --> 00:20:45,610
And the symmetry of these two

480
00:20:46,980 --> 00:20:49,200
will determine whether this is positive,

481
00:20:49,200 --> 00:20:51,360
in which case, it's
constructive interference,

482
00:20:51,360 --> 00:20:53,130
or whether this term is negative,

483
00:20:53,130 --> 00:20:55,593
which just means it's
destructively interfering.

484
00:20:57,030 --> 00:20:58,530
Okay, and this has been shown before.

485
00:20:58,530 --> 00:21:00,150
We're definitely not the first

486
00:21:00,150 --> 00:21:03,390
to find quantum interference
effects in molecular junctions.

487
00:21:03,390 --> 00:21:05,910
There's been evidence
of pi-pi interference

488
00:21:05,910 --> 00:21:08,580
where all the channels,
the HOMO, the LUMO,

489
00:21:08,580 --> 00:21:11,010
and other frontier orbitals
are pi in character.

490
00:21:11,010 --> 00:21:13,830
And so when the electron
crosses this junction,

491
00:21:13,830 --> 00:21:16,500
there's interference between
the different pi channels.

492
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:17,610
There's also evidence

493
00:21:17,610 --> 00:21:20,460
between different sigma
channels interfering.

494
00:21:20,460 --> 00:21:23,310
But what we showed is that
actually you don't need there

495
00:21:23,310 --> 00:21:26,940
to be, you know, only sigma,
only pi in certain cases,

496
00:21:26,940 --> 00:21:30,300
sigma and pi type channels can
interfere with it themselves,

497
00:21:30,300 --> 00:21:34,320
and this gives you a little
bit more kind of tunability

498
00:21:34,320 --> 00:21:36,690
and you can kind of
synthetically modify this

499
00:21:36,690 --> 00:21:37,680
a little bit more easily.

500
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:39,900
So the specific system we're going

501
00:21:39,900 --> 00:21:43,230
to be looking at is this
pyrazine molecule over here,

502
00:21:43,230 --> 00:21:45,390
which, again, it's very well known

503
00:21:45,390 --> 00:21:47,520
that if you bind linker groups

504
00:21:47,520 --> 00:21:49,830
to a benzene in the para position, again,

505
00:21:49,830 --> 00:21:51,480
that's kind of chemistry jargon,

506
00:21:51,480 --> 00:21:54,000
you bind a linker group
at one and at four,

507
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:57,090
and so this molecule
binds to gold through one

508
00:21:57,090 --> 00:21:58,440
and four positions,

509
00:21:58,440 --> 00:22:01,050
you're going to get
constructive interference.

510
00:22:01,050 --> 00:22:03,060
Whereas if you put a linker group at one

511
00:22:03,060 --> 00:22:05,550
and three, then you get
destructive interference,

512
00:22:05,550 --> 00:22:09,060
because of the symmetry of
the HOMO and LUMA pi orbitals.

513
00:22:09,060 --> 00:22:10,890
And what we show is that in pyrazine,

514
00:22:10,890 --> 00:22:14,730
we can actually flip this and

515
00:22:14,730 --> 00:22:17,880
reverse this trend and
then further engineer it.

516
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:18,840
So how does this work?

517
00:22:18,840 --> 00:22:21,720
So this is the work of
my student Hannah Skipper

518
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:23,340
